= Kinetics and Thermodynamics
- *Thermodynamics*: which process will occur spontaneously
- *Kinetics*: tells us about the rate of the reaction




*Ideal gas*: Distribution of energy is used to determine the fraction of molecules with $E_"trans" > E^‡$ (where $E_"trans"$ is translational energy and $E^‡$ is the activation energy).

Energy distribution function:

$f_(E)(E) = 2 (E / (pi ("RT")^3))^(1/2) e^(-E / ("RT"))$,
$P(E>E^‡) ∝e^(-E^‡ / ("RT"))$

*observed rate constant*
$k_"obs" = "constant" * e^(-E^‡ / ("RT"))$, ln $k_"obs" = -E^‡ / ("RT") + "constant"$

*The Arrhenius Equation*:Plot $ln k$ vs. $1/T$; the slope gives $-E_a/R$, enthalpy of activation
Two points: $ln(k_2 / k_1) = (E_a / R) (1 / T_1 - 1 / T_2)$

if flat slope, $E_a = 0$

*Transition State Theory*
$S arrow.l.r^(k_1)_(k_(-1)) S^* arrow^(k_2) P$, a transition state ($S^*$) of partial bond formation/cleavage

$K^* = k_1 / k_(-1) = [S^*] / [S]$,$(d P) / (d t) = k_2 [S^*] = K^* k_2 [S]$
